","1297":"1297","1197":"1197","1230":"1230","1294":"1294","1290":"1290","1317":"1317","Warwick, Warwickshire, England":"Warwick, Warwickshire, England","Newton Cheshire England":"Newton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Coughton, Warwickshire, , England":"Coughton, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","Newton, Cheshire, England":"Newton, Cheshire, England"},"nl":{"1225–1297":"1225–1297","1230–1294":"1230–1294","1255–1317":"1255–1317","1197–1239":"1197–1239","1239":"1239","1259":"1259","1225":"1225","1255":"1255","1297":"1297","1197":"1197","1230":"1230","1294":"1294","1290":"1290","1317":"1317","Warwick, Warwickshire, England":"Warwick, Warwickshire, England","Newton Cheshire England":"Newton, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Coughton, Warwickshire, , England":"Coughton, Warwickshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Newton, Cheshire, England":"Newton, Cheshire, England"},"en":{"1225–1297":"1225–1297","1230–1294":"1230–1294","1255–1317":"1255–1317","1197–1239":"1197–1239","1239":"1239","1259":"1259","1225":"1225","1255":"1255","1297":"1297","1197":"1197","1230":"1230","1294":"1294","1290":"1290","1317":"1317","Warwick, Warwickshire, England":"Warwick, Warwickshire, England","Newton Cheshire England":"Newton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Coughton, Warwickshire, , England":"Coughton, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","Newton, Cheshire, England":"Newton, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Holt","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, North German, Dutch, Danish, and Norwegian: topographic name for someone who lived in or by a small wood, from Middle English, Middle Low German, Danish, and Norwegian <i>holt</i>, or a habitational name from one of the many places called with this word. In England, the surname is widely distributed, but more common in Lancashire and Yorkshire than elsewhere."],"variants":[{"name":"Hohlt","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Ordell.","North German: variant of   Holt   with the additional <i>h</i> reflecting the lengthened vowel or a variant of   Hohl   with the addition of excrescent <i>-t</i>.","Scandinavian: variant of   Holt  ."]},{"name":"Holten","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Hjalmer, Lars, Nils.","Dutch (also <b>Van Holten</b>) and North German: habitational name from any of the places so called, from Low German <i>holt</i> ‘holt, copse, small wood’. There are two in the Dutch province of Overijssel and another near Oberhausen in the Rhineland.","Danish: variant of   Holt  ."]},{"name":"Holtan","meanings":["Norwegian: habitational name from any of numerous farmsteads so named, from the definite plural form of <i>holt</i> ‘small wood’ (see   Holt  )."]},{"name":"Holter","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Selmer, Hilmar, Knute, Lars.","Norwegian: habitational name from any of several farmsteads in southeastern Norway, from the indefinite plural of <i>holt</i> ‘holt, small wood’ (see   Holt  ).","North German (also <b>Hölter</b>): habitational name for someone from any of several places in Westphalia called Hölt and Holt (see   Holt  ). Compare   Hoelter  ."]},{"name":"Holtman","meanings":["Dutch: variant of   Holt   + <i>man</i> ‘man’.","Americanized form of German   Holtmann  ."]},{"name":"Holtmann","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Udo, Aloys, Hans, Heinz.","North German: variant of   Holt  ."]},{"name":"Holte","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Bjorg, Erik, Helmer, Hjalmer, Knute, Nels, Nordahl, Selmer, Swen, Thorvald.","North German: variant of   Holt  .","North German: habitational name from any of several places so named."]},{"name":"Hoult","meanings":["English: variant of   Holt  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Del","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Colloquial pet form of   Derek  , with alteration of the exposed <i>-r</i> of the short form to <i>-l</i> (  compare  Hal   and   Tel  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Derek","meanings":["From a Low German or Dutch form of <i>Theodoric</i> (  see  Terry  ), introduced into Britain during the Middle Ages by Flemish weavers, although it was not much used until a sudden explosion of popularity in the mid 20th century."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":34,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":65,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"John Del Holt I was born in 1225, in Newton, Cheshire, England as the son of Richard Holt. He had at least 1 son with Emma de Hatton. He died in 1297, in his hometown, at the age of 72."},"et":{"1225–1297":"1225–1297","1230–1294":"1230–1294","1255–1317":"1255–1317","1197–1239":"1197–1239","1239":"1239","1259":"1259","1225":"1225","1255":"1255","1297":"1297","1197":"1197","1230":"1230","1294":"1294","1290":"1290","1317":"1317","Warwick, Warwickshire, England":"Warwick, Warwickshire, England","Newton Cheshire England":"Newton, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Coughton, Warwickshire, , England":"Coughton, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Newton, Cheshire, England":"Newton, Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"1225–1297":"1225–1297","1230–1294":"1230–1294","1255–1317":"1255–1317","1197–1239":"1197–1239","1239":"1239","1259":"1259","1225":"1225","1255":"1255","1297":"1297","1197":"1197","1230":"1230","1294":"1294","1290":"1290","1317":"1317","Warwick, Warwickshire, England":"Warwick, Warwickshire, England","Newton Cheshire England":"Newton, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Coughton, Warwickshire, , England":"Coughton, Warwickshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Newton, Cheshire, England":"Newton, Cheshire, England"},"fr":{"1225–1297":"1225–1297","1230–1294":"1230–1294","1255–1317":"1255–1317","1197–1239":"1197–1239","1239":"1239","1259":"1259","1225":"1225","1255":"1255","1297":"1297","1197":"1197","1230":"1230","1294